scourses on "nature," including an incisive critique of the failures of queer theory to understand the social conflicts of the moment. By showing how reductivist explanations for sexual orientation lean on essentialist ideas about gender, Lancaster invites us to think more deeply and creatively about human acts and social relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPseudoscience. 0aScience news. 0aSex in popular culture. 0aSexual orientationxPhysiological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  abiological explanations.  aexpose.  agay and lesbian.  agender and sexuality.  agender norms.  agender roles.  aheterosexual fables.  ahistory of sexuality.  ahuman nature.  ajournalists.  algbtq.  amen and women.  anature.  anonfiction.  apopular culture.  aprimetime sitcoms.  ascience.  ascientific studies.  ascientific theories.  ascientists.  asex.  asexual desire.  asexual normalization.  asexual orientation.  asexual politics.  asexual relationships.  asocial history.  asocial relations.  asocial sciences.  atextbooks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093679940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936799/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles